[5]
Date: Mon 1 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: New York Times, Sat 29 Jun 2002 [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/29/international/americas/29BRIE3.html>

Honduras declares national alert
--------------------------------
Health officials have declared a national alert against dengue fever after
tallying 789 cases of the disease in the first 5 months of the year.
Officials urged people to clean their homes to stop the breeding of
mosquitoes that carry the potentially fatal disease. An outbreak in
neighboring El Salvador has claimed 4 [now 6] lives and led the authorities
there to declare a state of emergency in 4 regions.
******
[6]
Date: 1 Jul 2002 10:37:41 GMT-3
From: Luz Alba Fornells <luzalba@bioqmed.ufrj.br>
Source: Jornal O Povo Online 28 Jun 23h32min [translated & edited by JW]
<http://www.noolhar.com/opovo/ceara/152466.html>

The weekly report from the Ceara State Health Secretariat, published on 27
Jun 2002, lists 8651 confirmed cases of dengue in 2002, including 1903 in
Fortaleza (the state capital), with 36 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever
(plus 9 more suspected) -- 24 of them in Fortaleza -- and 6 deaths.
Juazeiro do Norte, a township 563 km from Fortaleza, has the largest number
of cases in the interior of the state, 549.
The deaths were 1 in Iguatu, 2 in Fortaleza, and 1 each in Barbalha,
Catarina, and Crateus. The number of cases has been diminishing monthly,
and is now comparable with that of the same period last year.
--
